			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hello all you EQ addicts!
<br />

<br />
Due to the overwhelming reaction to the "Root 101" thread I posted, I'm going to get in over my head and post a little more that I learned about one of our most potent spells, the surprisingly versatile "Root".
<br />

<br />
Today (early this morning, in fact) I had the pleasure of joining a group for an experience hunt in the Bandit Hills zone, east and a little north of Darvar Manor.  My group consisted of a 24 Shadowknight, a 25 Paladin, and a 21 Bard, with my 22 Cleric Sarai completing the group.
<br />

<br />
We stumbled on a camp of bandits, red to me, on the shore of a small lake.  I asked my tanks what the bandits conned to them, and found that they were, on the majority, white and yellow, with a smattering of dark blues.
<br />

<br />
Sounded good to me! <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
We set up our base camp, after a little recon, at a certain spot on the outskirts of the bandit camp.  We designated a puller (our paladin) and a peeler (our shadowknight).  Bard was there for buffs and support, and I was there to keep everyone breathing.  
<br />

<br />
The pulls were consistent, and the exp was good, ranging from 26-40K per kill.  It was easy.  I was getting bored.  
<br />

<br />
The sword-swingers would drop a bandit, and the puller would go get another one.  The new bandit would arrive, I'd drop a Field Dressing on the puller to bring his HP back up from the pull.  Then I'd drop a Minor Heal on the Shadowknight (our peeler, remember), and watch the bandit get beat into submission.
<br />

<br />
By the end of the cycle, the Shadowknight was usually only a bub from full, ready for another mob, and the Paladin (our puller) was ready to go get another.  The most exciting part of the group, for me, was telling them to stop so I could buff myself and the group.
<br />

<br />
Boooorrrriiiinnng.
<br />

<br />
This is where an idea struck.  Root stops mobs from moving.  Root generates aggro for the rooter, but nothing a decent Taunt-type spell won't overcome easily.  Root takes a good 30-40 seconds to wear off, unless the mob is hit.  I'm not doing anything while my group is pounding the current pull.
<br />

<br />
I'll just bet you can see where this is going.
<br />

<br />
I started to go find the next pull while the group was finishing off the mob.  After my cycle of Field Dressing the Paladin and Minor Healing the Shadowknight, I would run off and root another bandit.  Usually, by the time the first pull died, I'd be just coming back to the group, and our Paladin could simply go out, find the rooted bandit and smack him once.  The bandit would run (straight as an arrow, mind you) to me.  Before he could lay a hand on me, however, the Shadowknight would drop a "Taunt" on him, peeling him off.
<br />

<br />
Let me tell you, this new strategy had MULTIPLE benefits.
<br />

<br />
Our party had a constant flow of experience.  Since the mob had already been picked and rooted, it was only necessary for the puller to go up and hit it once to start the pull.  Also, the puller could simply follow the MOB to the killing ground.  No more moving the camera around to find the party.  All he had to do was follow along, since the MOB goes straight for the Rooter by the shortest means possible.
<br />

<br />
Also, the puller DOESN'T GET HIT during the pull.  The MOB's attention is all on getting to the source of the aggro (the Rooter).  After being released from the hold, it ignores the puller and goes straight to the Caster that rooted it.  One less heal for me to keep up with.
<br />

<br />
Also, I'M NOT BORED.  I'm healing.  I'm exploring, looking for new MOB's to root and prep for pulling.  Most importantly, I'M NOT STANDING STILL like a bump on a log.
<br />

<br />
Now, a few disclaimers:
<br />

<br />
This potentially is a recipe for disaster.  I didn't just "start" doing this arbitrarily.  I took the time to learn the camp, and to watch what MOBs went where.  I was careful to let my party know what was going on.  I tested my theory on nearby MOBs while my party wasn't already occupied with a pull.
<br />

<br />
I didn't take the time out to word-for-word explain to them what I had planned.  I think I'd have developed carpal-tunnel syndrome if I had.  I did make sure that everyone was prepared for it, though.
<br />

<br />
Please, for the love of the game, don't just spring this on an unsuspecting party.  If anyone in the group has a problem with it, DON'T DO IT.  You'll wreck the party and probably end up killing them.
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, all other things being equal, this was a use for the Root spell that I didn't see right off the bat, and the potential for increasing a group's xp intake is enormous.
<br />

<br />
Just thought I'd spread the word!
<br />

<br />
Antimone
<br />
25th Monk
<br />
The Ageless Knights of Avalon
<br />
Ferran's Hope
<br />

<br />
Sarai
<br />
22nd Cleric
<br />
The Ageless Knights of Avalon
<br />
Ferran's Hope</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
